<paragraph blockId="51.[151,1437,1818,2004]" lastBlockId="52.[151,1436,152,698]" lastPageId="52" lastPageNumber="53" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis box="[198,852,1899,1924]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Diagnosis from the original description and illustration</emphasis>
: Specimen incomplete, 
<quantity box="[1136,1197,1898,1924]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" unit="mm" value="2.0">2mm</quantity>
wide. Tentacles and branchiae absent in the specimen. Chaetae limbate; uncini MF:3–4 according to the text. MF as long as twice the accessory teeth; Sr narrow, with a well developed, acute SrP projected in the same direction of the MF; SrA not showed; LSr concave; AP divided in two rounded lobes, the upper larger than the lower lobe; AF absent; Bs slightly rounded on its lower margin, and thick; small angular protuberance between LOc and PP; a straight UOc; Cp with about 6 rows of teeth, according to figure.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="52.[151,1436,152,698]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">
<emphasis box="[198,337,272,297]" italics="true" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Discussion:</emphasis>
Since the original description is vague, material from the type locality need to be located, revised and redescribed to confirm characters and differences of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", McIntosh" authorityYear="1885" box="[945,1127,312,337]" class="Polychaeta" family="Terebellidae" genus="Pista" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="52" pageNumber="53" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="sombreriana">
<emphasis box="[945,1127,312,337]" italics="true" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">P. sombreriana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with other 
<taxonomicName box="[1272,1436,312,338]" class="Polychaeta" family="Terebellidae" genus="Pista" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="52" pageNumber="53" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[1272,1332,312,337]" italics="true" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Pista</emphasis>
species.
</taxonomicName>
However, since the type specimen is in such poor condition (Salazar-Vallejo, pers. comm.), material from the type locality needs to be examined; it may be necessary to designate a 
<typeStatus box="[979,1072,392,418]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">neotype</typeStatus>
or this species may be indeterminable, The plate by McIntosh (1887) has only one figure of an uncinus; neither the chaetae or body features were figured. According to the single figure, it has Cp with about 6 rows of teeth, which is greater than what is stated in the text. The AP is divided into two, and together with the well-developed and thick Bs, seem to be characteristic of this species, but uncommon in the other species from the Grand 
<taxonomicName authority="Londoño-Mesa, 2009" authorityName="Londoño-Mesa" authorityYear="2009" box="[1102,1222,552,578]" genus="Caribbean" pageId="52" pageNumber="4" rank="genus" status="new species, new genus">Caribbean</taxonomicName>
region. Thus, this species could be valid according to the type of uncini, but this needs to be corroborated by the type specimen or material from near the type locality.
</paragraph>
